WEBVTT

00:19.200 --> 00:21.509
[J the Bulgarian symphony orchestra:

04:11.320 --> 04:14.630
Nurse Evelyn. Nurse Evelyn!

04:14.800 --> 04:17.712
I have a message for you. In english.

04:36.920 --> 04:39.354
Now look, here's the list
of all the patients

04:39.560 --> 04:41.676
we've had in the ward in the last month.

05:57.720 --> 06:00.553
- You're Alexandria?
- Yes.

06:00.720 --> 06:04.315
Your... your note came in
and landed on my lap.

06:04.520 --> 06:05.953
I couldn't understand it,

06:06.120 --> 06:10.079
- it's written in gibberish.
- You didn't understand it?

06:10.240 --> 06:12.117
It's not for you.

06:15.400 --> 06:17.868
My name is Roy.

06:20.160 --> 06:22.958
- How'd you hurt your arm?
- I fell.

06:23.120 --> 06:26.795
- Me too.
- I was picking oranges.

06:29.120 --> 06:30.792
Is that so?

06:33.200 --> 06:34.872
How do you go to the potty?

06:35.040 --> 06:38.112
I don't.
They let me go right here.

06:38.280 --> 06:40.748
- In bed?
- That's true.

06:40.920 --> 06:42.956
I don't believe.

06:44.240 --> 06:46.549
Hey, Alexandria.

06:46.720 --> 06:49.951
Hey, did you know you're named after
Alexander the great,

06:50.120 --> 06:53.317
who was the greatest warrior
who ever lived.

06:53.520 --> 06:57.115
Yes, and my note is not in gibberish,
it's in english.

06:57.280 --> 06:59.350
Hey, I can see you.
Come on out here.

06:59.560 --> 07:02.870
- Whoa, whoa.
- I can see you hiding.

07:04.360 --> 07:08.876
Alexandria.

07:10.240 --> 07:13.198
Hey, did you know he was also
looking for a message?

07:16.000 --> 07:18.958
He's lost.

07:21.800 --> 07:23.711
He almost died.

07:24.680 --> 07:26.352
Separated from his army.

07:27.720 --> 07:30.188
Did he find the message?

07:30.360 --> 07:32.669
- What?
- Did he find the message?

07:32.840 --> 07:34.717
Alexandria the great.

07:34.880 --> 07:37.678
Ah, you know what? I'll tell you.
Just come in here.

07:39.320 --> 07:41.436
No, come on.
Grab that chair right there.

07:44.800 --> 07:47.394
All right. Don't break your other arm.

07:52.600 --> 07:54.431
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

08:00.080 --> 08:03.277
- What's in your box?
- Things I like.

08:05.000 --> 08:06.877
Things you stole?

08:07.040 --> 08:08.189
No.

08:10.000 --> 08:14.232
- A photo.
- Where'd you get the elephant?

08:15.880 --> 08:19.111
- My friend gave it to me at work.
- Hmm.

08:20.520 --> 08:22.158
He's from India.

08:23.680 --> 08:24.715
Look.

08:24.880 --> 08:27.997
This is my horse.

08:29.600 --> 08:31.830
And this is my father.

08:32.000 --> 08:35.708
Yeah? He's got the
same gap in his teeth.

08:35.880 --> 08:39.509
- It must run in the family.
- Yeah. And here is my house.

08:39.679 --> 08:41.193
- Oh, yeah?
- It was my house.

08:41.360 --> 08:43.669
- What happened?
- They burn it.

08:43.840 --> 08:47.549
- Who burned it?
- Angry people.

08:49.320 --> 08:50.992
Well, I'm sorry to hear that.

08:51.160 --> 08:54.835
- Mmm?
- I said I'm sorry to hear that.

08:55.000 --> 08:56.353
Angry people.

08:56.560 --> 08:58.994
I'm just sorry.
I'm sorry your house got burned.

08:59.160 --> 09:01.355
Why did Alexander

09:01.560 --> 09:06.759
didn't go from that buildings
on his horse?

09:07.560 --> 09:09.915
- If him was lost...
- What?

09:10.080 --> 09:13.197
Why did Alexander didn't go from

09:13.360 --> 09:19.549
that middle of the buildings,
from that buildings, on his horse?

09:20.440 --> 09:22.112
Well...

09:23.720 --> 09:27.508
First of all, he didn't have a horse...

09:27.680 --> 09:30.592
Because his horse
was killed in a battle.

09:32.800 --> 09:35.268
And he wasn't in the middle
of any old buildings,

09:35.440 --> 09:41.709
he was lost in the middle
of a vast desert full of orange sand,

09:41.880 --> 09:44.269
with only a handful of men.

09:46.320 --> 09:48.880
But they didn't have any water.

10:38.240 --> 10:41.676
My lord, all hope is lost.

10:41.840 --> 10:44.798
It seems your mighty army
shall finally be conquered.

10:44.960 --> 10:46.951
Not by the persians,

10:47.120 --> 10:50.829
but by our own greed
and gluttony for water.

10:51.000 --> 10:54.959
This helmet contains our last supply.

10:55.120 --> 10:58.430
Oh, king, I believe your wisdom
shall save us all.

11:07.640 --> 11:09.312
- Why?
- Why?

11:09.520 --> 11:10.839
Why?

11:12.160 --> 11:13.559
Why?

11:15.240 --> 11:18.357
Well, because there wasn't
enough water for all of them...

11:18.560 --> 11:21.074
- Hmm?
- It was Alexander the great's way of...

11:21.240 --> 11:24.198
Showing his army
that they were all equal. That...

11:24.360 --> 11:27.557
- That's stupid.
- Wh... what would you do better?

11:27.720 --> 11:30.154
Was Alexander throw the water

11:30.320 --> 11:34.916
instead to give
every soldier a little bit.

11:41.040 --> 11:44.555
Hey, come back tomorrow and I'm
going to tell you a different story.

11:44.720 --> 11:48.679
- An epic tale of love and revenge...
- Mm-hmm.

11:48.840 --> 11:50.910
- You know what epic means?
- No.

11:51.080 --> 11:53.719
I still got tightness here.
It's like I can't...

11:53.880 --> 11:57.919
It means a really long story.
And it's set in India.

11:58.080 --> 12:01.993
- All right, go on.
- I want you to examine me.

12:02.160 --> 12:04.993
You personally.
I'm not very well.

12:06.840 --> 12:08.159
Do you have a cigarette?

12:13.160 --> 12:15.276
The swelling seems down.

12:17.240 --> 12:19.674
I know how much it hurts.

12:19.840 --> 12:24.868
Someone should.

12:25.040 --> 12:29.033
In the next couple of weeks the pain
should abate, then one more operation.

12:29.200 --> 12:30.553
Like the last one?

12:30.720 --> 12:33.712
This is going to take
effort on your part. Know that?

12:33.880 --> 12:35.836
See?

12:38.880 --> 12:40.438
Ahh.

13:22.640 --> 13:23.993
Come on, then.

13:45.440 --> 13:48.159
- Be back before lunch.
- Ok.

14:06.440 --> 14:09.352
Alexandria. Get away from that ice.

14:09.560 --> 14:11.391
I see you. Get away from that ice.

14:11.600 --> 14:14.034
You're gonna get sick.
I want you to go play. Go.

14:14.200 --> 14:17.829
Next time I'll glue your lips to this
and carry you away.

14:23.960 --> 14:26.793
You're lucky it was
just a horse that got killed.

14:26.960 --> 14:30.430
Jumping off a train bridge
was suicide, too.

14:30.640 --> 14:32.517
If you were trying to impress her...

14:32.680 --> 14:36.719
- What did you...
- Sinclair already did a better job.

14:36.880 --> 14:39.075
You know, the actor.

14:40.200 --> 14:42.270
- The leading man.
- I know who he is.

14:44.160 --> 14:47.152
Every cloud has a silver lining,
that's for sure.

14:47.320 --> 14:51.074
- Take another card. That is a queen.
- Before my accident...

14:51.240 --> 14:53.231
The queen of hearts.

14:53.400 --> 14:56.198
I've had my leg
hacked off by savages,

14:56.360 --> 14:59.670
mangled by chariots,
sawed off by lumberjacks.

14:59.840 --> 15:04.197
I've even had a harpoon through it.
I'm working all the time.

15:09.000 --> 15:11.116
That is the two of spades.

15:11.280 --> 15:13.669
The studio is
trying to do right by you.

15:13.840 --> 15:16.274
- Mr sabatini.
- Take the money.

15:16.440 --> 15:19.796
Anyway, gags are not for you, Roy.

15:19.960 --> 15:22.269
- You're a college man.
- It wasn't me.

15:22.440 --> 15:25.671
- One cripple to another...
- It was little girls.

15:25.840 --> 15:30.231
- I didn't throw orange at you.
- No woman is worth suicide.

15:30.840 --> 15:33.035
Guy's a movie star,
for Christ's sake.

15:48.440 --> 15:51.034
Was you friend a pirate?

15:54.160 --> 15:56.515
Was your friend a pirate?

15:57.880 --> 15:58.915
Sometimes.

16:00.840 --> 16:03.035
Is that how he hurt his leg?

16:04.000 --> 16:08.391
No, he...
He does tricks for pictures.

16:08.600 --> 16:10.955
You know, flickers.

16:11.120 --> 16:13.190
- Hm?
- Moving pictures.

16:14.080 --> 16:18.596
- I never seen one.
- Ah, you're not missing much.

16:18.760 --> 16:21.228
Is that what you do, like your friend?

16:22.960 --> 16:25.872
- Just once.
- Hmm.

16:28.080 --> 16:30.389
Will you tell me the story now?

16:31.720 --> 16:34.359
- What story?
- The epic.

16:37.920 --> 16:39.592
All right.

16:41.600 --> 16:43.158
All right. Close your eyes.

16:46.400 --> 16:47.435
What do you see?

16:49.560 --> 16:50.879
Nothing.

16:53.600 --> 16:58.435
Rub 'em. Can you see the stars?

16:58.640 --> 17:01.632
Yes.

17:01.800 --> 17:04.314
It was a starry night.

17:04.520 --> 17:09.036
Four men waited impatiently
on a small island,

17:09.200 --> 17:12.032
surrounded by a calm sea.

17:12.200 --> 17:15.829
But that calmness was deceptive.

17:20.400 --> 17:25.792
For, at that moment,
an Indian with a bandaged thigh

17:25.960 --> 17:27.188
swam towards them.

17:40.640 --> 17:45.919
Luigi... is what true?

17:46.080 --> 17:50.631
Governor odious will execute
your twin brother tomorrow morning.

17:51.560 --> 17:53.630
My poor brother.

17:59.760 --> 18:02.593
In all, there were five of them.

18:02.760 --> 18:08.198
They had only one thing in common,
a hatred of governor odious.

18:10.000 --> 18:14.994
The first was an ex-slave, oftta benga.

18:21.920 --> 18:25.674
He and his brother
were born into slavery

18:25.840 --> 18:29.958
only to fill the coffers
of the evil governor odious.

18:32.240 --> 18:36.119
One day, while toiling in the fields...

18:49.520 --> 18:54.310
Heartbroken at his brother's death,
he freed the slaves

18:54.520 --> 18:57.990
and swore that he would be responsible
for governor odious' death.

19:02.240 --> 19:06.916
- I like him.
- Then, there was the Indian,

19:07.080 --> 19:10.993
who, whenever anxious,
always stroked his brow.

19:15.040 --> 19:17.554
The Indian was supposedly married

19:17.720 --> 19:21.838
to the most beautiful squaw
in the world,

19:22.000 --> 19:24.195
yet nobody had seen her.

19:24.840 --> 19:29.118
To verify this,
odious disguised himself as a leper.

19:29.280 --> 19:33.558
But when he saw her reflection,
he was smitten.

19:37.320 --> 19:41.916
Locking the doors to his wigwam,
the Indian stood guard.

19:42.080 --> 19:45.993
Little did he know,
he was guarding an empty home.

19:46.160 --> 19:51.075
For his wife had already been kidnapped
by the evil governor odious.

19:52.800 --> 19:55.872
But the squaw refused
to show herself to him,

19:56.040 --> 20:00.352
so odious had her thrown
into the labyrinth of despair.

20:05.080 --> 20:08.709
Eventually she realised
there was only one way out.

20:24.360 --> 20:26.078
While mouming his wife's death,

20:26.240 --> 20:29.437
the Indian took a blood oath
never to look at another squaw,

20:29.640 --> 20:33.553
and that he would be responsible
for governor odious' death.

20:38.200 --> 20:40.191
I like him, too.

20:40.360 --> 20:44.319
Luigi was an explosive expert.

20:46.880 --> 20:49.758
When odious heard about
the power of his new bombs,

20:49.920 --> 20:52.992
he had him publicly banished.

20:53.160 --> 20:54.309
On his return,

20:54.520 --> 20:59.435
Luigi discovered that everybody hid
from him, because even speaking to him

20:59.640 --> 21:02.234
was punishable by death.

21:02.400 --> 21:05.836
But when his own priest
refused to hear his confession,

21:06.000 --> 21:08.992
Luigi swore...

21:09.160 --> 21:13.153
That he would be responsible
for governor odious' death.

21:17.280 --> 21:21.671
Next, was the english naturalist,

21:21.840 --> 21:27.233
Charles Darwin.
He loved all living things.

21:27.400 --> 21:33.236
Creatures, plants... everything alive.

21:34.440 --> 21:38.797
Darwin was always accompanied
by his shy, brilliant, colleague,

21:38.960 --> 21:40.154
Wallace the monkey.

21:40.320 --> 21:42.629
What is that, Wallace?

21:44.160 --> 21:45.832
I don't know why flamingos are pink.

21:46.000 --> 21:50.152
Even though they had developed
many theories together...

21:51.440 --> 21:53.749
They were still
looking for something.

21:53.920 --> 21:56.036
What?

21:56.200 --> 22:01.638
- Butterfly.
- That's a good guess.

22:01.800 --> 22:04.951
In fact, a very specific butterfly...

22:05.600 --> 22:09.388
Called americana exotica.

22:10.560 --> 22:13.791
One day, odious sent them a dead one.

22:20.360 --> 22:22.191
Butterfly reef.

22:24.400 --> 22:27.949
This odious, it's, um...

22:28.120 --> 22:32.272
- Bad man?
- Oh, yeah.

22:33.320 --> 22:35.709
Butterfly reef.

22:35.880 --> 22:39.316
That's where governor odious
chose to banish our heroes.

22:41.160 --> 22:43.116
To mock them.

22:43.920 --> 22:46.514
Hoping, that in
their fight for survival,

22:46.680 --> 22:49.274
they would devour each other.

22:50.640 --> 22:53.518
So the buccaneers were trapped
on this island.

22:53.680 --> 22:56.240
What means a buccaneer?

22:56.400 --> 22:58.277
Well, it's like a pirate.

22:58.440 --> 23:01.238
Pirate and buccaneer,
it's like the same thing.

23:01.400 --> 23:03.436
But I don't like pirate stories.

23:05.040 --> 23:07.315
You're the one who asked
for a pirate story.

23:07.520 --> 23:09.351
Mm-mmm. No.

23:09.560 --> 23:11.710
- Yes you did.
- Mm-mmm.

23:12.720 --> 23:16.349
I just wanted to know if your friend
was, was a pirate.

23:16.560 --> 23:20.394
- Why?
- Because he has just one leg.

23:21.560 --> 23:23.232
Oh! Right.

23:24.640 --> 23:26.517
Well, yeah. It's not a pirate story.

23:26.680 --> 23:29.319
- It's a story about bandits.
- Mmm.

23:29.520 --> 23:33.195
In fact, our masked hero
couldn't even swim.

23:34.800 --> 23:37.314
I need to learn to swim.

23:41.200 --> 23:45.876
Finally, very little was known
about the gap-toothed masked bandit.

23:46.040 --> 23:49.350
- Like my father?
- Yes, your father.

23:51.400 --> 23:55.359
Except that he and his twin brother,
the blue bandit,

23:55.560 --> 23:59.189
had escaped execution
from the Spanish governor odious.

24:00.240 --> 24:04.518
Knowing that their chances of survival
were better apart,

24:04.680 --> 24:06.830
the two brothers separated,

24:07.000 --> 24:10.390
swearing that they would kill
governor odious.

24:15.200 --> 24:17.873
We must conceive a plan.

24:18.600 --> 24:22.639
I need to get off this island
and rescue my twin brother.

24:27.840 --> 24:29.671
What?

24:29.840 --> 24:31.717
What?

24:34.320 --> 24:35.548
All elephants?

24:46.080 --> 24:47.149
I say, we...

24:54.160 --> 24:56.116
I have an idea.

25:29.520 --> 25:33.593
Darwin! That was a great ideal!

25:50.840 --> 25:52.512
Come on, otta benga!

26:04.520 --> 26:06.272
Goodbye, my beautiful friend!

26:06.440 --> 26:08.954
Have a nice swim!

26:14.920 --> 26:18.674
Darwin! You are a genius!

26:18.840 --> 26:23.118
- Much obliged.
- Where do you get these ideas?

27:01.720 --> 27:03.790
What is it, my friend?

27:47.600 --> 27:53.197
How sad. The tortures of this world
have driven the poor man mad.

27:53.360 --> 27:57.717
Not true. He said he has
been sent by his mystic cult...

28:00.400 --> 28:03.995
To help us against governor odious
and his Spanish henchmen.

28:05.920 --> 28:09.037
This region was once a lush forest,

28:09.200 --> 28:12.158
alive with birds and sacred trees...

28:16.200 --> 28:18.270
But odious had them all burned down.

28:18.440 --> 28:23.275
He also says the birds
are safe inside his belly.

28:23.440 --> 28:27.035
But we must take care,
for only fittest shall survive.

28:27.200 --> 28:30.715
Tell him we have no use of a mystic.

28:33.920 --> 28:35.717
We are on a dangerous mission.

28:37.440 --> 28:40.910
We need to hurry to the fort
to save my twin brother.

28:41.080 --> 28:43.150
He will only slow us down.

28:48.360 --> 28:52.239
Fish, sefsior.

28:52.400 --> 28:55.039
Pescado!

28:58.200 --> 29:00.668
Pescado, serior, pescado!

30:25.040 --> 30:28.112
Stand aside, my friend.
Before you say "kaboom"...

30:29.240 --> 30:31.196
I have this door open.

31:14.240 --> 31:17.198
Forgive me, wise mystic,
for my disrespect.

31:18.080 --> 31:21.993
Undoubtedly, you have a flair
for warmongering.

31:23.160 --> 31:28.598
It would be my honour if you
consider joining us on our quest.

31:31.640 --> 31:33.517
We must save your brother!

31:42.640 --> 31:44.278
But first...

31:48.680 --> 31:49.874
A little test.

31:50.040 --> 31:52.918
- You can't stop there.
- I just wanna play a little game.

31:53.080 --> 31:56.436
I want you to go outside
and touch one of my toes.

31:56.640 --> 32:00.110
No, tell me the story.
What happened with the blue bandit?

32:00.280 --> 32:03.716
No, it won't take long. Just go
outside and touch one of my toes.

32:03.880 --> 32:05.359
Ok.

32:10.240 --> 32:12.629
- I'm touching your little toe.
- No.

32:12.800 --> 32:16.793
No, please don't tell me which toe
you're touching. I gotta guess.

32:16.960 --> 32:19.235
That's the whole point of the game.

32:19.400 --> 32:21.675
- All right...
- Uh-huh. I'm touching one.

32:27.040 --> 32:28.758
I'm touching one.

32:31.200 --> 32:32.952
You're touching my big toe?

32:34.840 --> 32:37.559
- Mm-hmm.
- Are you telling the truth?

32:38.600 --> 32:40.238
Mm-hmm.

32:43.520 --> 32:45.192
You can look.

32:48.360 --> 32:49.998
Great.

32:50.880 --> 32:53.235
Oh, I got that?

32:53.400 --> 32:56.437
What happened?
What happened with his brother?

32:56.640 --> 32:58.631
- Did he save him?
- No, no, no, no.

32:58.800 --> 33:01.030
- Were you telling a story?
- Uh-huh.

33:01.200 --> 33:04.033
No, no, no. Were you
telling the truth just now?

33:04.200 --> 33:06.839
Ye... no. I was telling the truth.

33:07.000 --> 33:09.514
You just said no,
you weren't telling the truth.

33:09.680 --> 33:11.238
No, I tell it.

33:11.400 --> 33:13.960
- Were you telling the truth?
- Yeah.

33:14.120 --> 33:16.759
- When you just touched my toe?
- Uh-huh.

33:19.080 --> 33:21.389
- You little liar.
- No.

33:24.240 --> 33:27.198
Alexandria, were you lying to me?

33:28.080 --> 33:30.071
I touch your big toe.

33:31.360 --> 33:32.873
We need to hurry!

33:34.400 --> 33:36.789
Do you want me
to finish the story?

33:38.560 --> 33:41.996
The masked bandit arrived
at the chandelier hall too late.

33:44.040 --> 33:46.838
Odious had already
tortured his brother and crew...

33:47.920 --> 33:49.638
And hung them.

34:06.880 --> 34:08.632
All right, that's it.

34:08.800 --> 34:11.757
It's not a circus.
It's not a playground for all your...

34:11.920 --> 34:14.831
Please! Are you listening to me?

34:15.000 --> 34:16.194
Get otta here!

34:17.239 --> 34:18.275
You leave her alone.

34:18.440 --> 34:21.273
- Come here, baby.
- Get off! Goddamn...

34:21.440 --> 34:24.955
Aw, no, no, no, sweetheart.

34:25.120 --> 34:27.395
Come here, come here. Come on.

35:26.080 --> 35:29.516
- Dad? Dad?
- What do you want?

35:29.680 --> 35:32.274
- He's doing it again.
- Stop that? Leave him alone!

36:01.920 --> 36:04.195
- What's that?
- Food.

36:04.360 --> 36:07.352
- Where'd you get it?
- The chapel.

36:12.720 --> 36:16.349
I'm sorry I shouted at you.

36:16.560 --> 36:19.836
- I was angry.
- No problem.

36:20.840 --> 36:23.195
- Are you trying to save my soul?
- Hmm?

36:23.360 --> 36:25.271
Are you trying to save my soul?

36:27.640 --> 36:29.437
- Did you understand me?
- What?

36:29.640 --> 36:31.392
Did you understand what I meant?

36:31.600 --> 36:32.828
What you said?

36:33.000 --> 36:35.958
I said, "are you trying
to save my soul"?

36:36.120 --> 36:38.759
- Give me that.
- What mean that?

36:38.920 --> 36:40.592
The eucharist. It's, uh...

36:42.440 --> 36:43.668
What?

36:43.840 --> 36:45.956
